75","1517–1581":"1517–1581","1520–1605":"1520–1605","1522–1559":"1522–1559","from 14 April 1550 to 23 May 1550":"from 14 April 1550 to 23 May 1550","1550":"1550","1581":"1581","before 1514":"before 1514","1514":"1514","about 1517":"about 1517","1522":"1522","about 1514":"about 1514","Abt 1520":"about 1520","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1575":"1575","about 1522":"about 1522","1605":"1605","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England","of Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cramphorne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>crampe</i> ‘curved’ +  <i>horn</i> ‘horn’.  Compare  Crunkhorn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crunkhorn","meanings":["English: nickname: unexplained. Perhaps a variant of   Cramphorn   formed with Middle English  <i>crunkel(d)</i> ‘wrinkle(d)’ rather than  <i>crampe</i>,  <i>crumpe</i> ‘curved, bent’. Compare  <i>Crankhorn</i>, apparently similarly formed with  <i>crank</i> ‘bent, crooked’: Thomas James Crankhorn, 1754 in   IGI   (Clerkenwell, Middx)."]},{"name":"Crampin","meanings":["1  English: contracted form of   Cramphorn  .","2  English: nickname possibly from Middle English  <i>crampoun</i> (Old French  <i>crampoun</i>) ‘cramping iron, grappling iron’, possibly for a maker or user of such an implement."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":24,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":118,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Cramphorne married Mrs. Cycelie Cramphorne before 1514, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died from 14 April 1550 to 23 May 1550, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England."},"et":{"–from 14 April 1550 to 23 May 1550":"–14. aprill 1550 kuni 23. mai 1550","–1550":"–1550","1514–1575":"1514–1575","1517–1581":"1517–1581","1520–1605":"1520–1605","1522–1559":"1522–1559","from 14 April 1550 to 23 May 1550":"14. aprill 1550 kuni 23. mai 1